{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.04,0.69,0.21,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107502"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2396"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl is rushed to the Emergency Department following accidental ingestion of her grandmother\u0027s Webster-packed medications. The medications included atorvastatin, aspirin, amitryptyline and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn arrival, the child is observed to be having a generalised tonic-clonic seizure which started six minutes ago and is unresponsive. She has no significant medical history including no previous history of seizures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents should be given?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxazepam","Phenytoin","Midazolam","Diazepam","Levetiracetam"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most urgent medical emergency to treat here is the seizure, as prolonged seizure can lead to permanent neurological damage. According to the Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical Practice guidelines: first-line treatment for seizure is a benzodiazepine such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E which can be given via the intravenous, intramuscular or buccal routes at 5 minutes. A repeat dose should be given after another 5 minutes if the child is still seizing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for seizure management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for drug-induced seizures due to proven reduced efficacy in these patients and concerns that its sodium channel blocking action may increase the risk of arrythmias in these patients. However, it is a second line agent for afebrile seizures in children from other causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is a suitable drug to treat paediatric seizure; however, midazolam (given by any route) is more effective in controlling seizure than diazepam. For this reason, it would be less correct than midazolam - though a suitable choice clinically if diazepam is the only benzodiazepine accessible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is another second line agent (IV or IO) for afebrile seizures in children. After two rounds of benzodiazepines, or 10 minutes of treatment, this agent could be given. If this was a non-drug induced seizure, phenytoin can be given if seizure persists for another 5 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive treatment is recommended for any seizures of \u0026gt;5 minutes (or unknown) duration, where there is cardio-respiratory compromise, or in the case of any suspected causative pathology. The seizure needs to be treated immediately, as it is likely caused by amitriptyline toxicity and is thus is unlikely to self resolve. Once the seizure is controlled, treatment should move to other priorities including further treatment of tricyclic, paracetamol and other medication toxicities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A benzodiazepine is the first-line management for afebrile seizures in children.","Active management of seizure is recommended for seizures of \u003E5 minutes (or unknown) duration, in cardiorespiratory compromise, or in the case of suspected causative pathology."],"references":["Afebrile seizures. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines [Online]. 2020; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Afebrile_seizures/","Smith R, Brown J. Midazolam for status epilepticus. Aust Prescr 2017;40:23-5. February 1, 2017. Available from: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2017.005","Chen HY, Albertson TE, Olson KR. Treatment of drug-induced seizures. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 2016 Mar;81(3):412-9. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4767205/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T15:08:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T15:09:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"898"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107502"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n